segments.text: And so since his daddy had the car a lot and he had the car, we decided to room together and that was okay with Wally and he found another room.
Describe what that room, how was it furnished?
What luxuries did y'all have in that room?
We had a double-decker army cot-type bed with cotton mattresses about six inches thick.
We had two oak desks.
Two oak chairs, a wash basin, a towel rack, a closet.
The room itself was, I'd say, 10 by 12.
Now, by what method did you all decide who slept on the top and who on the bottom?
I don't remember that.
I slept on the bottom, but I don't remember how we decided that's the way it was going to work.

It could have been that Walter knew that if he ever got drowned out, the guy on the bottom bunk had better get up and turn his mattress over very quickly, or he was going to be sleeping on a soggy mattress.
Now, I would not accuse Walter of that.
But he volunteered to take the top bunk.
And I will go no further than that.
And how long was it before you ran into any of the traditions of the questions and the whipping out and all that?
Right away.
You all had been oriented on that out at the air base?
Out at the air base.
OK.
We went through practice drills on that.
And when we got back to Hart Hall and some of the upperclassmen came in early, they would try to see how effectively we had been taught, I'll put it that way.
So that all the Aggie sports were represented in Hart Hall.
Every sport.
Who were, for you as a fish, who were some of the celebrity famous Aggie athletes here in the fall of 48?
You mean in my class or just in Hart Hall?
No, in Hart Hall.
Well.
The juniors, seniors.
There was Bob Smith, Rapid Robert, All-American fullback.
He wasn't All-American at that time, but I knew Bob from playing football and
running track against him when he was at Lamar High School in Houston.
Now he was a year or two ahead of you?
He was one year ahead of me.
One.
We were kind of spare on standout athletes at that time.
Yeah, that was kind of a down time, wasn't it?
It was, because in the fall of 48 in football, for example, we went 0-9-1.
And Homer Norton was the?
Homer Norton had been let go the year before.
Harry Steitler was the football coach.
Typist, that's S-T-I-T-E-L-E-R.
Correct.
And did Colonel Andy come over to your room much in those early days?
Colonel Andy would pass through about every other day just to see if
Everybody was getting settled in and you know how things were going.
Colonel Andy let you do your own thing.
He was available for guidance if you wanted it.
He was a father figure to every one of us.
Now you were in an outfit.
What outfit was it?
Core outfit was it?
It was the 7th Regiment which was a composite regiment which consisted of the
day students from Bryan and College Station, as well as the athletes.
Now you said regiment, not company.
Regiment.
Regiment.
Seventh regiment.
Composite regiment.
Now we, in Hart Hall, we had two companies.
We had A Athletics, which, and they divided it.
That consisted of football players and basketball players.
And
B Company Athletics was everybody else.
Did y'all have a nickname, your company?
No, no, just the athletes, that's what they called us.
All right, describe what it was like to, let's see, how did you register academically?
Did y'all stand up?
We registered out at Bryan Field.
Okay, you went through the lines and all?
As part of the...
freshman orientation process.
Right.
Describe going to your first classes.
What was your impression the first few days?
It was, we knew by that time where our buildings were.
The upperclassmen
had seen to that.
And they were helping us out as well, so that we wouldn't wander around in on a gall, all that kind of business.
And our classes were nearby.
The farthest classes we had were down by the old water tower.
In fact,
The new water tower is there to this day, just a different type of water tower.
And down behind that water tower there were a lot of old World War II barracks that they had pulled out of Bryan Field and had brought out there to the college and rehab and cut up into classrooms.
And a number of our classrooms were down there.
But we had history in the academic building.
We had math and economics in Pfeiffer Hall along with the bats.
The place was full of bats.
Pfeiffer Hall had fireplaces and chimneys in it.
Fireplaces were boarded up, but if you'd be on the blackboards you could hear the bats in there.
That's where we had our classes.
Do you remember what your academic load was in number of hours that first semester?
Yes, sir.
We carried 19 hours.
And you were at that point an engineering major?
No, I was business.
I changed my mind to business before I got here when I saw that I was going to have a pretty busy schedule with athletics and trying to put the time that I felt I should into academics.
I was very academically oriented.
Describe going to classes the first days and your impression and what the faculty attempted to do and say.
We had an economics prof, I don't remember his name, but the first thing he said was, and he wrote it on the board,
He said, if you can teach a pig to say supply and demand, you have an economist.
And would you believe that showed up as a question on the first major quiz?
And we had Screamin' Al Nelson for history.
Make believe I didn't know him.
Describe.
Screamin' Al Nelson was about as hard shell a Republican as you could come across.
An extremely brilliant man.
I don't believe there was a book in Cushing Library that he hadn't read.
You could never put anything over on him except for one thing.
If you wanted to get out of a boring lecture, all you had to do was raise your hand and say, Dr. Nelson,
My dad said that Roosevelt pulled us out of the Depression, and he would take off like a skyrocket.
Now, he would yell about that more than anything else, wouldn't he?
Oh, absolutely.
He would get up on his desk.
He would kick the books and the inkwell and everything else off his desk.
He would start marching back and forth on that desktop, stomping and shouting, and the
Other people, other professors who had classes would very nicely come and shut his door so they wouldn't have to listen to him echo up and down the halls of the academic building.
That was the funniest thing I ever ran into in my life from a prof.
But in fact, he was an effective teacher.
Oh, he was.
I mean, you learn history.
You learned it.
pretty much on your own.
What he taught you was ancillary stuff.
You got your test questions out of the textbook.
And he didn't put up with any goofing off, did he?
No nonsense.
Absolutely no nonsense.
What about some other from that first semester, if you can remember?
We had Dr. Doak for biology.
Dr. Doak was a brilliant
a scientist, a Casper Milk Toast type of man.
But there wasn't anything about biology that he didn't know.
And he taught us a lot.
He was very quietly effective in his own way.
And a full three hours of lab every week, I bet.
A full three hours of lab.
No frog dissections.
We had that in high school.
And while I'm on that subject,
You had asked me earlier how I felt my high school had prepared me.
It was very obvious compared to what some of the other students absorbed or what they knew.
We were all required to take Algebra I.
Most of them had had, not most, but half or so, had had two years of mathematics.
addition, subtraction, multiplication.
Very few of them had geometry.
I had had two years of algebra, a year of plain geometry, a semester of solid geometry, a year of trig, and chemistry and physics.
I took the whole nine yards.
And I felt real sorry for some of these
young fellows that came out of smaller schools that didn't have the opportunity to learn all those things that I did.
What were, for you and your new friends that had the same kind of attitude you have, what were your basic guidelines about going to class, class behavior, and so forth?
The guidelines were
you're expected to go to class.
That was all that was said about it.
And behavior, you're a young gentleman, you behave yourself in class, and we did.
I mean, we were athletes, and athletes are probably a little more rambunctious than the average student, but we were also kind of no-nonsense guys.
I knew what we were there for.
And I just thought of this.
You were also a comparatively rare commodity to be freshman on that campus, weren't you?
On the main campus.
An oddity is not done again to describe it.
We were unique.
So there weren't many freshman sections of anything.
We were the freshman section of everything.
Now, the
The curriculum and classes that I'm describing to you are the classes that the business freshmen went to.
Now, some of the engineering freshmen, they would go to our English and math and history classes, and then they'd go to their specialized classes.
As you get worked into this academic routine,
Where did you and your buddies go when you had a break, when you had some unscheduled time?
The Y.
What did you do over there?
Shoot pool, drink coffee.
Were you a coffee drinker when you got to A&M?
Oh, hardly.
But it didn't take long.
I became a veteran coffee drinker.
Had you been a pool shooter before you got here?
No.
My roommate, Walter Evans, taught me that.
He taught me pool.
He taught me snooker.
And there was a snooker parlor up above Doc Lipson's drugstore at Northgate.
Really?
At the corner of Northgate and College Main, catty-cornered across from the post office.
And we would go up there and play the game, the occasional game of snooker.
And then...
If you wanted to just kind of go somewhere and rest, relax, where would you go?
Go to the library.
You could go back in the stacks and get lost.
I would have been surprised if that hadn't been your answer.
And did you ever go back in there and go to sleep, literally?
Take a nap?
I didn't.
I was too curious as to what they had back there.
And I wanted to find out about it.
And of course, some of the stacks were restricted.
depending upon your classification and what you were studying.
Now, and the library was almost a sacred place in terms of no hazing or anything like that.
Is that right?
Absolutely.
There was no, none of that sort of thing went on in the library.
It just wasn't done.
Make believe that I had not been in Cushing at that era.
Describe it.

As I recall, you went up to the steps into a large room and around the periphery of the room were bookcases of various and sundry different types of books and then back behind the main desk were what we call

of research and then of course there were, I don't recall whether there were two or three levels of stacks up behind the main desk, but that's where you did the specialty research and you'd go to the card index and look up what you wanted to research and turn the card in.
Somebody would go get the books for you.
Okay, then you went to chow.
What was...
I digress.
I remember the ornate light fixtures in the ceiling in the library.
Back to the, what was the routine like when you and your buddies went to the chow hall?
Describe a typical meal and how it was done.
We didn't have revelry like they did over in the Corps.
the Corps would form in a quadrangle and they would march to Belkin Hall for their breakfast meal.
Depending upon when our class was, our first class, we would more or less straddle down to Sedesa.
When we first got there, the upper class had the idea, well, we will march all the freshmen down there.
Well that lasted for about a week because the upperclassmen didn't want to get up and march down there with us anymore than we wanted to march ourselves.
So that kind of died on the vine and we found our own way down there if we felt like going to breakfast.
And I was always a big breakfast eater and I always went down there and took my books with me and went from there to my first class.
But y'all didn't have all that routine as to who serves it or anything?
Well, the people who served it were waiters who did not have...
But I mean, you didn't have, as a fish, you didn't have to take care of an upperclassman's plate or anything like that.
We had to make sure that the upperclassmen were fed first before we ate.
Oh, okay.
Okay.
And of course, the meals were served family style and big bowls and big platters and that kind of thing.
But no, as far as having to actually serve the upperclassmen, no.
What was your impression of Aggie food, dining hall food?
It was, like they said in the cadence,
a freshman privilege is to eat all you can.
And I was a chow hound.
And I thought the chow was great.
Now, the pork chops would get a little greasy.
And the bull neck was not always the best.
It was, shall we say, chewy.
But I thought it was good.
And I didn't notice anybody ever turning their nose up at anything that was served.
All right, so y'all didn't,
Did you athletes march either to lunch or supper?
We did not march to a meal after the first week.
But y'all did have a table where you were supposed to sit each of the three meals.
We did.
We sat by outfits.
And unless your sport was in season,
season, then we had what was called a training table, where you didn't get all that greasy bull neck, you got a better quality mainly meat.
Who were the key seniors at your table?
Jack Quirey, who was the company B commander.
Spell his name.
Q-U-I-R-E-Y.
He is a retired school administrator,
At East Bernard, Texas.
He came from around East Bernard.
Ed, chairman of the board, Bluebell Creamery.
Cruz?
Ed Cruzy.
From Brenham?
From Brenham.
His brother, Howard Cruzy.
was a freshman classmate.
They were both swimmers.
And Herschel Maltz, M-A-L-T-Z, was a baseball player from Houston.
Houston McCarty, a track man.
He was class of 51.
The upperclassmen kind of rotated in and out, but pretty generally stayed with their freshmen in their ramp or in their sport.
Did you fish athletes attempt any dining hall pranks, jokes, good bull?
No, we didn't attempt any, but we were the focus of a lot of them because
We would have to, for example, during football season, if you wanted your kush, which was dessert, if you wanted your kush, you had to stand up in your seat and give kush call.
And have you ever heard the kush call for Rice Institute?
What comes out?
No.
Oh.
Well, that was another one.
That was the brief version.
The long version was, in a high falsetto voice, you would say, the loudest possible voice, Rudy toot toot, Rudy toot toot, we're the boys from the Institute.
We don't smoke and we don't chew and we don't go with girls that do.
Our class won the Bible.
And if the upperclassmen were satisfied that you gave a satisfactory push call,
Fish, lemmings, saddle, eat your kush.
If they didn't like it, you'd give it again.
Now, did you acquire a nickname?
No, I did not acquire a nickname.
Because most people did, didn't they?
Quite a few did, but I was just plain old Paul.
What about back in the dorm that freshman year?
Were there some Good Bull jokes, pranks?
Oh, we had Good Bull sessions.
Yeah, we had a lot of them.

One of the more memorable ones, the upperclassmen had told us that what you freshmen need to do is go out and scout the country and find a good outdoor crapper so that you can put it up on top of the bonfire and you put your names and all that on it and you'll be recognized.
They didn't tell us what we would be recognized for.
So a group of us, Billy Bless, me, Don Graves, Marshall Sorrell, Jody Zurn, may have been one other.
I can't recall right now.
But we started scouting around out in the countryside, principally down Wilbur Road because
Septic tanks were unheard of in those days.
Everybody had an outdoor jar.
And we found what we thought would be the ideal crapper and we scouted it out and we decided how we were going to make our approach.
There was a road that went behind the house about a hundred yards away from the house.
There was a barbed wire fence along the road.
we were going to lay the fence down, sneak in at night.

We had a couple of tuba sixes, two three-pound mauls, a double handful of 20 penny nails, and we were going to sneak up to that outhouse and whack, whack, whack, wrap those tuba sixes up on that outhouse, put it up on our shoulders, and sail out of there back to Marshall Sorrell's
Model A Ford, on which he had built a platform extension in the back.
We were going to set that thing up there.
And I had a Boy Scout bugle.
And we were going to go all over the campus blowing this bugle, letting everybody know that we had stolen the perfect outhouse.
Well, what they didn't tell us was that it was the band's privilege to put the outhouse on the bonfire.
And we had been set up by the upperclassmen in Hart Hall.
And they told us, yeah, paint your names on there with shoe polish.
Well, we got the recognition.
And it was from the big bull himself, Hayden L. Boatner.
Who would later be famous in Korea.
At Chejudo.
No, Koji Island.
The prisoner of war.
We felt that that was a perfect spot for Colonel Boatman.
But anyhow, we had our plan laid out, and in the dark of night, we went out to execute it.
We took wire cutters, and we cut the fence, and we laid the fence down, and we snuck up about 100 yards through this pasture.
And when we got about 20 yards from the house, this joke yard dog comes out from underneath the house.
We had not seen a dog while we were out there.
Of course, he was always up underneath the house sleeping.
That's why we hadn't seen him.
And we got up there real quick.
We kicked him away and racked up and put those two to sixes on there.
Jody Zurn went up to the door to the outhouse, swung open.
The lights came on in the house.
And we were...
just a few steps away from being intercepted.
Jody took two steps forward to close the outhouse door.
There was a concrete lip out over the pit.
Jody stepped too far onto the concrete lip and went ka-chunk down into the pit.
Jody was a little guy anyhow.
Oh, that's a price.
Yeah, and he was standing on his tiptoes just back there keeping his chin

above all the crud and I don't remember who reached down in there to pull him out, but the rest of us started running with this outhouse and we figured somebody was helping Jody and they were on their own.
We got back to the Model A and put the outhouse on there and here came the junkyard dog and the guy who
lived in the house, and he, blam, blam, fired a couple of times, and we got out of there.
He evidently had notified Colonel Boatner that a group of students had stolen this, so Boatner started a campus-wide search, and it didn't take him long.
Hart Hall was just the next door down from Ross Hall, which was where all the Bulls had their offices, and with our names on there, it
did not take a Philo Vance to figure out who the culprits were.
And we were called on the carpet.
And he put his finger in our belly button and said, I want a new outhouse back on that man's property by sundown.
I don't care how you do it.
I just want it out there.
Yes, sir.
And by sundown, we had a new outhouse.
How did you do it?
We scrounged lumber.
We got the upperclassmen to loan us some money so we could buy lumber.
We felt they owed it to us since they'd set us up.
And somebody sketched some plans out very quickly, you know, who had an outhouse of their own at their place out in the country.
We just did it.
And took it back and put it in place.
Took it back and put it in place.
Did your buddies tease y'all or anything?
No, they just kind of snickered.
And we said, we're going to get you guys.
We're going to get you.
And how did y'all get them back?
I don't know that we ever did.
Well, one guy we did get back, he was a crapperman.
And we knew that he had been one of the instigators behind trying to get us to steal the perfect apple.
And we waited until he went in there to take a crap.
And we snuck around and walked the door on his side, came back around to my side,
We had what was referred to in those days as a nigger chaser, which was a pyrotechnic and you would light it and it would go all over the place and then explode.
We figured we gave him enough time to drop his britches and sit down and we opened the door and threw this light chaser in there, locked the door,
And there he was, spinning around him with his pants down below his ankles.
And we could hear him hollering and screaming.
And we let him sweat it out for about 15 minutes, and somebody went back up there and unlocked his door.
Now, the mention of the outhouse causes me to ask, what did a fish in your year, what did you all do about bonfire?
